<subSubSection id="C3058B8FFF8B0458FFF8FC4DFCA2FC7E" box="[113,802,906,931]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF8B0458FFF8FC4DFCA2FC7E" blockId="61.[113,1089,906,1618]" box="[113,802,906,931]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF8B0458FFF8FC4DFE85FC7F" bold="true" box="[113,261,906,931]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">
<typeStatus id="54A466A6FF8B0458FFF8FC4DFF29FC7E" box="[113,169,907,931]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C1FA387FF8B0458FE85FC4AFDEAFC7E" authority="Fabricius, 1803" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1803" box="[268,618,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Lygaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="566" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="festivus">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF8B0458FE85FC4AFE3AFC7E" box="[268,442,908,931]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Lygaeus festivus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8EA5F5FF8B0458FE48FC4DFDEAFC7E" author="Fabricius" box="[449,618,907,931]" firstAuthor="Fabricius" pageId="61" pageNumber="566" refId="ref64358" refString="FABRICIUS J. CH. 1803: Systema Rhyngotorum secundum ordines, genera, species, adiectis synonymis, locis, observationibus, descriptionibus. Reichard, Brunsvigae, vi + 314 pp + Emendata and Index." type="book" year="1803">Fabricius, 1803</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, here designated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3058B8FFF8B045BFFF8FC7FFCBDFB6E" lastPageId="62" lastPageNumber="567" pageId="61" pageNumber="566" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF8B0458FFF8FC7FFC80FB4F" blockId="61.[113,1089,906,1618]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF8B0458FFF8FC7FFF7CFC0C" bold="true" box="[113,252,953,977]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Description.</emphasis>
Body large (♂♂ 15.50–19.60 mm, 
<specimenCount id="9D19138DFF8B0458FDEDFC71FD03FC0D" box="[612,643,951,976]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566" type="female">♀♀</specimenCount>
16.00–18.90 mm).Antennae in both sexes long, always longer than pronotum, sometimes even longer than combined length of head and pronotum; antennomere 1 longer than antennomere 2 (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FD3DFC3CFCB1FBCF" box="[692,817,1018,1042]" captionStart="Figs 93–98" captionStartId="66.[151,188,1574,1593]" captionTargetBox="[214,1061,228,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-10@66.[205,1070,217,1500]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="Figs 93–98. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803). 93 – female; 94 – male; 95–96 – fore leg (95 – large male, 96 – small male); 97 – ventral surface of profemur. 98 – Physopelta (Neophysopelta) gutta gutta (Burmeister, 1834), ventral surface of profemur. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740017/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 93−94</figureCitation>
); there is great variability in length of antennae among specimens. As an example, the length of antennomeres of three large and three small males are given here: Large males (mm): 1 – 7.13, 6.59, 6.43; 2 – 6.32, 6.05, 5.56; 3 – 3.35, 3.19, 2.11; 4 – 3.89, 3.62, 3.59; small males (mm): 1 – 4.27, 4.86, 4.8l; 2 – 3.89, 4.32, 4.37; 3 – 2.11, 2.32, 2.38; 4 – 3.19, 3.24, 3.08.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF8B0458FF19FB5CFCA8FAAF" blockId="61.[113,1089,906,1618]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">
Callar lobe only slightly gibbose, without sexual differences (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FC8CFB5CFC00FB6F" box="[773,896,1178,1202]" captionStart="Figs 93–98" captionStartId="66.[151,188,1574,1593]" captionTargetBox="[214,1061,228,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-10@66.[205,1070,217,1500]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="Figs 93–98. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803). 93 – female; 94 – male; 95–96 – fore leg (95 – large male, 96 – small male); 97 – ventral surface of profemur. 98 – Physopelta (Neophysopelta) gutta gutta (Burmeister, 1834), ventral surface of profemur. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740017/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 93−94</figureCitation>
). Labium reaching between mesocoxae. Profemora sexually dimorphic; in females more slender, with smaller number of small denticles; in small males profemora similar to those of females (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FC30FB1CFBB4FB2F" box="[953,1076,1242,1266]" captionStart="Figs 93–98" captionStartId="66.[151,188,1574,1593]" captionTargetBox="[214,1061,228,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-10@66.[205,1070,217,1500]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="Figs 93–98. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803). 93 – female; 94 – male; 95–96 – fore leg (95 – large male, 96 – small male); 97 – ventral surface of profemur. 98 – Physopelta (Neophysopelta) gutta gutta (Burmeister, 1834), ventral surface of profemur. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740017/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 93−94</figureCitation>
). Ventral surface of profemora with short longitudinal furrow limited to its apical third; basal two-thirds medially convex with numerous denticles on the entire surface (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FC0EFADCFC59FAEF" box="[903,985,1306,1330]" captionStart="Figs 81–84" captionStartId="62.[151,188,963,982]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,218,945]" captionTargetId="figure-10@62.[151,1126,217,945]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Figs 81–84.Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male.81 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×); 82 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (70×); 83 – ventral surface of profemur (32×); 84 – detail of peritreme (150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 84), 0.5 mm (Figs 81–83). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740011/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 83</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FC6AFADCFB81FAEF" box="[995,1025,1306,1330]" captionStart="Figs 93–98" captionStartId="66.[151,188,1574,1593]" captionTargetBox="[214,1061,228,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-10@66.[205,1070,217,1500]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="Figs 93–98. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803). 93 – female; 94 – male; 95–96 – fore leg (95 – large male, 96 – small male); 97 – ventral surface of profemur. 98 – Physopelta (Neophysopelta) gutta gutta (Burmeister, 1834), ventral surface of profemur. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740017/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">97</figureCitation>
). Protibiae ventrally unarmed (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FE0DFAFCFD81FA8F" box="[388,513,1337,1362]" captionStart="Figs 93–98" captionStartId="66.[151,188,1574,1593]" captionTargetBox="[214,1061,228,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-10@66.[205,1070,217,1500]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="Figs 93–98. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803). 93 – female; 94 – male; 95–96 – fore leg (95 – large male, 96 – small male); 97 – ventral surface of profemur. 98 – Physopelta (Neophysopelta) gutta gutta (Burmeister, 1834), ventral surface of profemur. (Photos: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740017/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 95−96</figureCitation>
). Peritreme of metathoracic scent glands longitudinal, crescent-shaped, projecting both anteriad and posteriad (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FD45FA9CFC9CFAAF" box="[716,796,1370,1394]" captionStart="Figs 81–84" captionStartId="62.[151,188,963,982]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,218,945]" captionTargetId="figure-10@62.[151,1126,217,945]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Figs 81–84.Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male.81 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×); 82 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (70×); 83 – ventral surface of profemur (32×); 84 – detail of peritreme (150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 84), 0.5 mm (Figs 81–83). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740011/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF8B0458FF19FABCFEB8FA2F" blockId="61.[113,1089,906,1618]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">
Pygophore (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FE99FABCFE0DFA4F" box="[272,397,1401,1426]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 85−88</figureCitation>
). Ventral rim slightly concave, rounded; lateral rim more elevated than ventral rim, strongly rounded, descending towards dorsal rim. Lateral rim infolding only slightly sloping into the genital chamber; anal tube wide, long, reaching middle of genital chambre (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FF55FA1CFEACFA2F" box="[220,300,1498,1522]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Fig. 86</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF8B0458FF19FA3CFB81F98F" blockId="61.[113,1089,906,1618]" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">
Parameres (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FE98FA3CFE12F9CF" box="[273,402,1530,1554]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 89−92</figureCitation>
). Parameres horizontal, their apices approaching and standing opposite each other, their apical portions bent dorsally, apex hook-shaped, pointed (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FB98F9DCFF39F98F" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Figs 91−92</figureCitation>
), distinctly surpassing ventral rim of pygophore (see in lateral view − 
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF8B0458FC2FF9FCFC75F98F" box="[934,1013,1594,1618]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="566">Fig. 88</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF60888CFF88045BFF1EFC05FCABFBD6" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740011" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5740011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740011/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" startId="62.[151,188,963,982]" targetBox="[151,1126,218,945]" targetPageId="62">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF88045BFF1EFC05FCABFBD6" blockId="62.[151,1126,963,1036]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">
Figs 81–84. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FA387FF88045BFF77FC02FD99FC0B" authority="(Fabricius, 1803)" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[254,537,963,982]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Kmentia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="festiva">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF88045BFF77FC02FE03FC0B" box="[254,387,964,982]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Kmentia festiva</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF8EA5F5FF88045BFE05FC05FD93FC0B" author="Fabricius" box="[396,531,963,982]" firstAuthor="Fabricius" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" refId="ref64358" refString="FABRICIUS J. CH. 1803: Systema Rhyngotorum secundum ordines, genera, species, adiectis synonymis, locis, observationibus, descriptionibus. Reichard, Brunsvigae, vi + 314 pp + Emendata and Index." type="book" year="1803">Fabricius, 1803</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, male.81 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 47×); 82 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (70×); 83 – ventral surface of profemur (32×); 84 – detail of peritreme (150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 84), 0.5 mm (Figs 81–83). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF88045BFF3DFB5DFCBDFB6E" blockId="62.[150,1126,1179,1619]" box="[180,829,1179,1203]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Female internal genitalia were described by DUVIARD (1975).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3058B8FFF88045BFF1FFB7DFD6AFA2E" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF88045BFF1FFB7DFD6AFA2E" blockId="62.[150,1126,1179,1619]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF88045BFF1FFB7DFE10FB0E" bold="true" box="[150,400,1211,1235]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C1FA387FF88045BFE1FFB7AFE70FB0E" authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" box="[406,496,1212,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Kmentia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF88045BFE1FFB7AFE70FB0E" box="[406,496,1212,1235]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Kmentia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A258B96DFF88045BFE7EFB7AFDD8FB0E" box="[503,600,1212,1236]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FA387FF88045BFD5AFB7DFCE9FB0E" authorityName="Hussey" authorityYear="1929" box="[723,873,1211,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="566" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Physopeltinae">Physopeltinae</taxonomicName>
because of the strongly S-shaped intersegmental sulci between the abdominal sternites. It differs in several characters from the other genera of the subfamily, warranting its placement in a tribe of its own – 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FA387FF88045BFB92FB3AFF41FAEE" authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="trib. nov." tribe="Kmentiini">Kmentiini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A258B96DFF88045BFF4CFADDFEA7FAEE" box="[197,295,1307,1331]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" rank="tribe">trib. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
: labium reaching between mesocoxae; callar lobe weakly gibbose in both sexes; ventral surface of profemora in both sexes with only short longitudinal furrow limited to its apical third, basal two-thirds medially convex with numerous denticles on the entire surface; protibia in both sexes unarmed; and structure of the male genitalia (parameres horizontally positioned, their apices approaching and standing opposite each other (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF88045BFCF5FA5DFC4AFA6E" box="[892,970,1435,1459]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
), bent dorsally in their apical portion, apex hook-shaped, pointed dorsally (
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF88045BFC8DFA7DFCFBFA0E" box="[772,891,1467,1491]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Figs 85, 87</figureCitation>
), distinctly surpassing ventral rim of pygophore (see in lateral view − 
<figureCitation id="1324C481FF88045BFD07FA1DFD5DFA2E" box="[654,733,1499,1523]" captionStart="Figs 85–92" captionStartId="65.[112,149,1296,1315]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-196@65.[113,1088,219,1277]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Figs 85–92. Kmentia festiva (Fabricius, 1803), male. 85–88 – pygophore: 85 – intact, dorso-posterior view (magnification 50×), 86 – dissected, dorsal view (55×), 87 – intact, posterior view (50×), 88 – intact, lateral view (60×). 89–92 – paramere (different orientations; 150×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 89–92), 0.5 mm (Figs 85–88). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740015/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Fig. 88</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3058B8FFF88045BFF1FFA3DFF7CF98E" pageId="62" pageNumber="567" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA0D804FF88045BFF1FFA3DFF7CF98E" blockId="62.[150,1126,1179,1619]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="B96B0416FF88045BFF1FFA3DFE96F9CE" bold="true" box="[150,278,1531,1555]" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Etymology.</emphasis>
This new genus is named in honour of my friend and colleague Petr Kment (Department of Entomology, National Museum, 
<collectingRegion id="49DB16E6FF88045BFD15F9DDFD68F9EE" box="[668,744,1563,1587]" country="Czech Republic" name="Praha" pageId="62" pageNumber="567">Prague</collectingRegion>
) with thanks for his help. Gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
